Objectives
The purpose of the current study is to assess and evaluate the potentially inappropriate medications among the geriatric patients at the tertiary care Hospital of Larkana Sindh which is the biggest Hospital in the Northern Part of Sindh.
Methods
The descriptive cross-sectional study was conducted which included the 500 patients aged more than 60 years. The data was collected from the patients' case charts and the questionnaire distributed among the patients. BEERS′ criteria was used to detect the frequency of chronic disorders in geriatric patients and appraise the polypharmacy.
Results
The male patients were 42.6% and the female patients were 57.4%. The inappropriate medication use (IMU) was observed among 22.6% patients. Inappropriate antibiotics were seen in 35.39%, Benzodiazepine 28.32%, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) 15.04%, cardiovascular system (CVS) drugs 12.39% of patients. Parenteral route of administration was observed in 70.04% of patients.
