Under-5 mortality was higher in mothers who were poor, illiterate and working either as a professional/technical worker or as an agricultural worker. Children whose mothers were illiterate and had less than two years of the birth interval had the highest under-5 mortality. Younger mothers (aged less than 20 years) lost more children. Under-5 deaths were more among those mothers who were poor and had less than two years of birth interval. The child mortality was significantly high in poor households with low birth interval.
