The results showed that the unemployment rate and out-of-pocket payment (OOP) had a strong relationship with healthcare resources. So, a 1% increase in unemployment rate leads a $ 138 decrease in health expenditure per capita and a 1% increase in OOP is accompanied with a $ 12 decrease in health expenditure per capita (p-value<0.01). In this regard, countries having an unemployment rate more than 5% and OOP more than 25% indicate $ 260 health expenditure per capita less than countries with OOP less than 25% and an unemployment rate less than 5%.
Conclusions
