number = "2",
pages = "214 - 217",
year = "2019",
issn = "2213-3984",
doi = "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cegh.2018.06.004",
url = "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S221339841830068X",
author = "S.K. Verma and Nidhi Kaeley and Sohaib Ahmad and Minakshi Dhar and Abhimav Chhabra",
keywords = "Breast carcinoma, Metabolic syndrome, BMI, Post-menopausal women",
abstract = "Background
Breast carcinoma is one of the commonest cancer in women accounting for major health burden worldwide. Metabolic syndrome is a known risk factor of non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) as well as breast carcinoma. APRI (Aspartate aminotransferase to platelet ratio index), a known non-invasive marker of liver fibrosis and steatohepatitis has never been studied in patients of metabolic syndrome with breast carcinoma. Breast carcinoma has various modifiable risk factors such as obesity and alcohol consumption. Hence, we compared APRI score in patients with breast carcinoma in order to establish a possible correlation.
